rComments: Seminars were well run and informative. Your conception of the subject material will be challenged and deconstructed. Many writing assignments that get progressively harder and longer so you have to be ready to put in the work. Don't take this course if you're looking to slack off.

I joined the seminar class, A History of Race in America, with Professor Wayne this semester. He is quite knowledgeable in this topic, and was able to facilitate thorough and thought-provoking discussions that were always enjoyable, even if you didn't participate too much. He's very nice, although his essay topic wording can be a little confusing.

Professor Wayne is a really interesting guy. He's a bit of an acquired taste but if you take the time to talk to him he's super open and really nice. In seminar courses he talks for a long while but it's always very insightful. I took his seminar about race in America and thoroughly enjoyed it even though the readings are mostly his works.

Attended his undergraduate and joint undergraduate/graduate courses in 1985!!!  One of the best professors I have had. Clear and engaging, his lectures were a joy. But perhaps the best thing about Michael Wayne is that he listens to his students and takes their input seriously.

I graduated in 2002 and took three classes with Wayne. In my opinion his class alone is worth the tuition payment. I am now a secondary school teacher and teach American History, my knowledge of the course comes straight from Wayne. He is an amazing lecturer, his classes were always interesting and he was always clear.

I enjoyed how he sat in front of us and lectured for 2 hours, with only paper notes and a list of topics to guide him. He's very opinionated and will sometimes talk about his own personal views regarding political issues but it didn't detract from his lectures; it's interesting to hear a perspective rather than an inept attempt to be unbiased.

He has a very old-fashioned lecturing style. He does not use Powerpoint. His lectures have no bells and whistles. He sits at the front of the class and talks about his subject. It's a much more enriching experience to listen to his lectures than it is with most other professors.
Prof Wayne is great! Excellent lecturer who manages to make subject matter interesting and appealing. Really enjoyed his class, would take another class with him as lecturer.

Very relaxed and clear. Reasonably (but not always) approachable. My only complaint is that he often makes pretty wild comparisons between the past and current events. I know enough history to understand that these comparisons are, unless made carefully, misleading at best. In any case, I don't see how they make his class more enriching.
Best prof I've had (twice) at U of T!
very good

Lectures were awesome. Prof is an awesome guy. Loved the fact that later papers were not accepted because it forced me to get them done on time. Tutorials were every 2 weeks which wasn't so effective. No official textbook for course but there are course readers which I found useless, so attending lectures was KEY!
Best professor at UofT I've had so far.
Lecturing style is very straightforward, clear. Nice guy, unpretentious. NO late papers accepted.

He was a good lecturer.  This course should be renamed "The African American History Course" as 95% of the lectures involved race relations, which while being an important topic, got a tad repetitive.  I would have liked it more if he involved more discussion on gender, rise of american cities, and America as viewed by other countries,& pop culture

Professor Wayne is a great instructor; he explains himself clearly, and is extremely well-organized. His lectures were entertaining. Heavy reading load, but material was exceptionally relevant and interesting. Socratic method in tutorial (if he leads them) encourages original thought.

The readings were BORING! Also, having tutorials every second week sounds good, but I think I would've felt more comfortable to participate in discussion if it was EVERY week. If it was every week, then I would've known my classmates and the TA a lot better. It would have made things  less impersonal. Wayne, however, is  a fabulous lecturer!
Best prof I've had so far! Funny and well-spoken. I will DEFINITELY be taking his other courses!

A wonderful lecturer-the best I've had yet! BUT the course reading were, in my opinion, NOT the greatest-especially in second semester. If professors really want their students to analyse their readings-LESS IS MORE. I've found most of the articles to be reiterating the same thing. Thumbs down on the readings-LESS IS MORE!!!
Engaging, organized, and enlightening.  I had a year with pretty dismal profs, and Prof. Wayne made my year bearable.  UofT needs more profs like him, a lot more like him.

Definitely lives up to the bill as one of U of T's best professors/lecturers. Lectures are easy to follow, clear, insightful and highly engaging. And he does it all with no aids or required textbook...
final mark ends up like 10% below what it should be
Best prof i've ever had..he put so much passion into his lectures and offered so much in addition to lectures..i would definitely take another course of his!
Great professor. Very organized and enthusiastic lectures. Goes beyond the required 2 hour lectures by showing movies and playing music outside of class time.
booooooring
I took his class years ago (1995) and he was one of my favourite professors in all my 4 years!  He was extremely knowledgable and eager to help us take a better interest in the subject.
I thought Rick Halpern was a great complement to Wayne.  They work well together.

Although on the surface he doesn't appear to be a prof, once you hear his lectures you'll see he is one of the best profs at U of T.  Incrediably knowledgeable with lots of interesting lectures.  A great class, it sucked when Halpern took over.
Took his class years ago (1993?) but I remember him as my favourite professor.  Clear, funny, intelligent...
Great hair! lol.  funny and excellent lecturer.  Expects a bit much of the upper year students though
No Comments
love the voice!!  really smart, subtle sense of humor, seems genuinely nice...an excellent lecturer...
Lectured History as though reading it from a child's story book.  A delight!
best prof ever at UofT, great lecturer, fair marker, and very helpful!
He's not just a great professor - he's like an older brother.
Best prof I've had so far. Clear & simple speaker. Makes it  easy to understand.
really hard, but he's the best prof in the history department, hands down.
DEMANDING COURSES, BUT FEEL EXTREMELY HONOURED TO HAVE HIM AS A PROF GREAT HAIR
No Comments
I love his crazy hair and his lectures are great!
He's the Bob Dylan of the history department
No Comments
One of the best Prof I had in UofT.
great lectures, easy to follow, doesn't even need his notes! wicked!
